{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"11bddc17-d7a9-40ea-9471-1f446172c0bc","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe project file is clean — nothing wrong there. The 2-4s overhead is the **dotnet CLI cold-start tax**: every `dotnet build` invocation spawns a new process, loads the MSBuild engine, and re-evaluates the project graph from scratch. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a persistent MSBuild server in-process.\n\n## Recommendations (most → least impactful)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nKeeps the process warm and watches for changes — no startup cost after the first run:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Ensure the MSBuild Server is enabled (.NET 8+)\nThe MSBuild server reuses nodes across CLI invocations. It's on by default in .NET 8, but verify these env vars are **not** set:\n```bash\n# These DISABLE the server — make sure they're unset:\n# DOTNET_CLI_DO_NOT_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n# MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1\n```\n\n### 3. Use graph-based builds (multi-project solutions)\n```bash\ndotnet build /graph\n```\nThis evaluates the project graph up front and avoids redundant evaluations. Less impact for a single project, but significant for solutions.\n\n### 4. Add a `Directory.Build.props` to suppress unnecessary work\n```xml\n<!-- Directory.Build.props -->\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Skip generating a runtime config on every build if not needed -->\n    <GenerateRuntimeConfigurationFiles>false</GenerateRuntimeConfigurationFiles>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n### Summary\nFor **quick edit-build-test cycles**, `dotnet watch build` is the single biggest win — it eliminates the MSBuild startup cost entirely and matches Visual Studio's behavior of keeping a warm build server. The MSBuild Server (recommendation #2) helps when developers prefer manual `dotnet build` invocations.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"73d9ecb3-f807-4062-8f0c-1d5ec018d0ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've already verified analyzers aren't the issue and incremental build targets work correctly.\n\nThe key insight from the report is: \"The overhead seems to come from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\"\n\nThis is a well-known issue. Visual Studio is fast because it keeps an MSBuild server process running in the background that maintains the project graph in memory. When you run `dotnet build` from the CLI, each invocation:\n\n\n1. Starts a new dotnet process\n2. Loads the MSBuild engine\n3. Evaluates the entire project graph (SDK resolution, imports, etc.)\n4. Only then checks if anything needs building\n\nThere are a few practical solutions. Using `dotnet build-server` in .NET 8+ enables an MSBuild server that persists across builds. For the most impactful improvement to the development workflow, `dotnet watch` keeps the process alive and watches for file changes, rebuilding incrementally without the startup overhead each time.\n\nFor multi-project solutions, the `/graph` flag or `<BuildInParallel>true</BuildInParallel>` can help parallelize builds. The `/nodeReuse:true` flag keeps MSBuild nodes alive between builds, though this is typically the default behavior. In .NET 8+, the MSBuild server is enabled by default, but it's worth verifying it hasn't been disabled through environment variables.\n\nThe most practical approach boils down to using `dotnet watch build` for development to avoid startup overhead entirely, and ensuring the MSBuild server is actually enabled in your environment.","outputTokens":1324,"requestId":"C789:199131:1020396:140AD5B:69FFD735"},"id":"09ea62f0-ccec-4860-bf8b-d2e00e056ba1","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:54:41.232Z","parentId":"d1d480b3-27f8-45c0-9365-538fe4504db2"}
